,At the outset, let me state that they are the institutions of national importance, promoted by the Government of India. They serve national priorities and interests and purport to lead Indian organisations to the acme of business effectiveness. They are spread over every nook and cranny of India. They are located in Kolkata, near the bay of Bengal; in Sirmaur amidst the verdant, mountains of Himachal Pradesh; in Kashipur situated the sugarcane belt of Uttrakhand; in Udaipur the lake city of Rajasthan; in  Gaya the religious city were the Hindus go to pray for the peace of the spirits of their ancestors; in Bangalore the Indian silicon valley; in Sambalpur, the heartland of tribal belt in Orissa; in Amritsar the holiest place of the Sikhs; in Indore, Raipur and Nagpur representing central India;  in Khozikode in the God’s own country; in Lucknow the capital of Uttar Pradesh; in Ahmedabad the emerging manufacturing hub; in Jammu, in the state of Jammu and Kashmir struggling to overcome the menace of terrorism; in Rohtak situated close the capital of India; in Tiruchirappalli in the southern India; and, in Shillong in the beautiful North East. Thus, they are located in mega cities, state capitals and small towns.,Harvard developed famous case study method for teaching business. Its focus on knowledge was less and the emphasis on decision making was high. On the other hand, other business schools stressed subject knowledge delivered through traditional lecture method, which was complemented and supplemented by other methods like group discussion, project work, and experience sharing, etc. Men involve recruitment and development of faculty. There were no ready made business education teachers available. Therefore, teachers of related subjects, like economics, finance, banking, etc. were recruited and practicing managers were also selected to bring realism in the classroom.,The client system recruits the graduates and benefits from executive education and consulting provided by an institute. With a view to help the business school to connect with itself, the client system provides avenues for research and instructional development, such as cases, industry notes, and white papers.,The IIMC,November 2, 2018,Business School Period:,The FF provided for the foreign exchange requirements of international collaborations of the two Boston based schools and two IIMs. It included provisions for International Teachers Programme (ITP) for Indian faculty, visits by American faculty, library, some equipment, professional fees to the architect in the case of the IIMA and other miscellaneous expenditure. Such financial support was valuable in creating the foundation of world-class business schools in India.,By the end of the 20,In 1975 the High Court of Uttar Pradesh declared the election of Prime Minister invalid and created an unprecedented problem for her. She then imposed emergency. In 1976, the 42,century, the public sector IIM fully transformed itself and became an established business school. The three directors – Prof KRS Murthy, Prof Pankaj Chandra and Prof G Raghuram – from IIMA have brought it closer to the classical business school model. Additionally, its location helped it to become an integrated business school.,The IIMs are founded to professionalise Indian management (American business schools were also established for the same purpose). Further, they intend to make leaders (any higher education institution worth its salt has the same claim). They aim at developing competencies in management and its functional areas. Finally, they attempt to apply management theories in the Indian context and advance concepts and models suitable to India (Initially they borrowed concepts and models of management from the United States and it has not stopped yet). Their mission is still work in progress.,The first three universities established by the East India Company in 1857 in India at Kolkata, Chennai, and Mumbai were basically affiliating universities and were primarily concerned with curricular development and conduct of examinations. They did not engage in teaching. Rather, teaching was done in the affiliated colleges under the curricula prescribed by the university. As the East India Company was a commercial organisation, it had limited objectives in promoting and providing higher education to Indian youth. The three universities were modelled on the pattern of the University of London, England, which was basically an examining university.,The British knowledge enterprises were Oxford and Cambridge universities, characterised by scholarship, residential status and tutorial method. The three Indian universities chiefly aimed at producing a breed of ‘Babus’ ( a clerical class) and a few professionals. They had disciplines like arts, law, medicine and civil engineering to begin with. The examining university – popularly known as affiliating university today – was a cost effective solution to higher education; and, it thus suited the British Raj. True to their mission, these universities performed well and produced a slew of government servants, lawyers, doctors and intellectuals. They hardly focussed on research and development, even at a later stage of their existence. Compared to their international peers, they were at best laggards in rigour, quality and personal development of students. Later, more and more colleges were added to these universities. Decades later, teaching was added to them. However, external examination remained the fulcrum of their activities. Interestingly, Mumbai University today has more than 500 affiliated colleges. There are few government universities in India that are not non-affiliating ones. As a result, their maximum energy goes into curriculum development and conduct of examinations. Research and innovation do take a back seat in their scheme of things.,and IIT,The Client System, Location and Institutional Development,__ATA.cmd.push(function() {
					__ATA.initDynamicSlot({
						id: 'atatags-26942-60d06c0424c22',
						location: 120,
						formFactor: '001',
						label: {
							text: 'Advertisements',
						},
						creative: {
							reportAd: {
								text: 'Report this ad',
							},
							privacySettings: {
								text: 'Privacy',

							}
						}
					});
				});,The IIMs are faculty-driven institution. The Director has a secondary role and acts on the recommendations of the faculty. When a director tries to be assertive, there is a high degree of resistance from the faculty. Earlier trade unions were quite active over there, now they are either non-existent or less active. However, staff members have permanent jobs and do have a say in the running of the institution.,Bombay,The campus has exposed grey stone buildings, with a concrete base. Each building has long, huge and wide corridors. There are gardens and pergolas all around. Buildings have accidental social spaces among them. The idea was to have buildings and classrooms amidst gardens.,A vital link connecting the business school and the client system is the location of the school. In fact, location is so important that most universities are named after them; for example, Oxford University, Paris University, Calcutta University, Allahabad University, etc. A city affects the growth and development of an institution and vice versa.,The Idea of a National Institution,Most faculty have tenured positions. They get tenure within a short period of two to three years. Research and extension are not remuneratively attractive to them. As a result, the mission of creating knowledge in the Indian context is put in the dust. Lack of extension activities has reduced the involvement of faculty with neighbouring communities. Ironically, while the IIMs are nationally oriented, they are oblivious to their surroundings. The IIMs are faculty-driven institutions. Till now the Board has not shown deep involvement in increasing their competitiveness. The IIMs operate in a placid environment and faculty-driven model has worked for them. The problem arises only when they are compared to the leading business schools in the western world.,__ATA.cmd.push(function() {
                __ATA.initVideoSlot('atatags-370373-60d06c0427cce', {
                    sectionId: '370373',
                    format: 'inread'
                });
            });,Strategic Options before the Third Generation IIMs,The idea behind the IIMs was to be free standing schools. Their separation from the university system had its own cost. They unwittingly developed a narrow perspective. They did not benefit from other disciplines as a typical business school would in a traditional university. In addition, they did not commence under graduate programme in management. In the United States, the MBA was the mainstay of management education. Nevertheless, under graduate education in management soon occupied a major place. As a result, BBA programme did not flourish in India.,Location and Infrastructure,Courtesy: IIM Indore,September 2, 2018,In a typical case, a decision maker develops three alternatives and analyses their pros and cons, positives and negatives. No alternative is perfect or proven. Therefore, choices create uncertainty and ambiguity for a decision maker, which in turn lead to anxiety, angst, intra-self conflict and sometimes inaction. No case tries to map this reality. Decision making without personal stakes and with personal stake is quite different. The former has little emotional appraisal, while the latter has intense emotional appraisal. Thus, making recommendations is easy, while doing things is daunting.,There was a watertight compartment between general management group and sectoral management group. General management faculty did not understand government and public sector management. On the other hand, sectoral management faculty had no interest in corporate management. They used to teach only a few electives in the PGP and students had hardly any curiosity for them.,He was adept at simplifying complex matters and his students appreciated that. He wrote a book on “Extremely short cases” to aver his viewpoint. The book consisted of cases running into only three to four pages. The power of those cases was not analysis, but synthesis. Strategy for him was about integration and wisdom, not number crunching. To help his students, he also did a book titled “Dictionary of Strategic Management”, which became quite popular.,The IIMs are government-owned, but they behave like private business schools as they charge full tuition fees from their students. It was not always so. Only in the beginning of the third millennium, the IIMs, on the instruction of the Government of India, started charging full tuition fees from their PGP students. The intake of students increased majorly around this time and it was not possible for the central government to subsidise the fees of all students. Thus, the IIMs are not much different from private business schools in India. However, they remain a government body in many other matters.,The Second Director of the IIMB,Elite universities like Oxford and Cambridge did not feel the need to develop and impart management education. It might be because of two reasons. Firstly, they treated management education as a vocational education and were not interested in it. Secondly, there was no fixed body of knowledge and the discipline of management was not developed yet. Therefore, there was no question of teaching a discipline that did not exist at all. It is interesting to note that the departments of business administration were established at Oxford and Cambridge universities quite late in the 20,Heavy industry on the one hand and surging private sector on the other necessitated the need for highly trained and capable cadre of technologists and managers. As a result, a few Indian Institutes of Technology were established. Similarly, a felt need emerged to found an American business school like institution in India.,The academic leaders of IIMs have no control over the location of their institution. Nevertheless, they have to face the consequences of a poor location. Hence, they respond to it in a variety of ways. For example, the Indian Institute of Management, Lucknow decided to open a satellite campus at Sector 62, Noida. Similarly, the Indian Institute of Management, Indore opened a facility in Mumbai. In the same vein, the Indian Institute of Management, Kozhikode operated a centre in Kochi.,sovereign,In 1959, two path-breaking reports were published, scathing business education in America. These were the Ford Foundation Report and the Carnegie Report. American business education till the late fifties is described as ‘trade education’ and a ‘wasteland of vocationalism’. It required revival and new direction. The main criticism of these reports was lack of research and scholarship among the professors of business schools. They pointed out that too much focus on practice led to the poor development of theoretical understanding of management and its allied subjects. In addition, they also emphasised the need for understanding the people dimension of business. Thus, the coverage of social sciences in the business education curriculum increased.,The period between the mid-70s and the mid-80s was politically turbulent but economically subdued. It started with the imposition of the Emergency by the Prime Minister Mrs Indira Gandhi. For which she was outed in the general election of 1977. However, the Janta Party – the new political formation of varied political groups – could not provide a stable government. In 1979, general election was held and Mrs Gandhi returned to power with a thumping majority. Unfortunately, her bodyguards assassinated her in 1984. It led to one of the worst communal riots in the history of India.,In the first half of the twentieth century, American business schools were in continuous search of mission, method and men. The mission is concerned with curriculum, while the method is related to the pedagogy of the programme. Business schools debated the kind of managers that wish to develop and the subjects they need to teach to accomplish their goals. They also identified a number of courses to be taught. However, there was quite a diversity in different curricula.,72.550048,The Indian Institute of Social Welfare and Business Management founded in 1953 was the first business school in India. However, it could not influence the direction and dynamism of management education in India. Circa 1954, business schools were established at the universities of Delhi, Mumbai, Madras and Andhra. They offered part time MBA programme for practicing managers. As a result, their impact was limited. In addition, these were basically a department under the Faculty of Commerce in respective universities. It further stunted their growth and development.,secular,nd,The Twin Start-up IIMs,Anup K Singh, PhD,century and early 20,Indian Institutes of Management: Pre-IIM Period Higher Education,October 12, 2018,I just examined differences between the IIMC and IIMA. At the same time, they had several common threads. Obviously, they were the first business schools of India, after the American MBA model. They became the role models for the future business schools. Initially, both schools concentrated on management development programmes so that they can establish linkages with their client system as well as create awareness about the PGP. They also worked hard to get the support of the business organisations in placing their PGP students. In mid-sixties, most corporates did not feel the need to hire professionally trained managers. Thus, the IIMs had to create a market for them.,Emotional appraisal is based on deeply held beliefs, life experiences and assumptions that override the facts and information presented by a situation. People tend to rely more on their positions. Sometimes they appraise the situation more objectively, other times they do not. Likewise, their emotional appraisal of a situation – positive or negative – can help them or hurt them. It may cut either way.,Its strategy was to attract high quality faculty and provide them with a conducive intellectual environment. It initially focussed on the training of professional managers at three levels: junior, middle and senior. Training, in turn, led to consulting assignments. Professors from the MIT helped the IIMC to strengthen management development programmes and to design post graduate programme (PGP)  in management. Its faculty had strengths in economics and finance, quantitative methods and behavioural sciences. Several faculty had foreign degrees or were senior managers in different business organisations.,A major breakthrough happened when Harvard University decided to open a business school in 1908. Harvard established a paradigm for business education. Firstly, it is a two year post graduate programme. Secondly, it is a general management programme. Thirdly, it is experiential in nature. Lastly, it is taught by both academicians and practitioners. Most business schools follow these principles, even today. After Harvard Business School was established, it provided legitimacy as well as credibility to business education and a slew of business schools were founded. By 1922, the United States had more than 159 business schools. Most of them were private business schools.,The  Indian Scenario,Madras,In order to meet the diverse objectives of the Institute, two faculty streams were created: general management group and sectoral management group. The general management group had faculty from the traditional areas of management education, such as statistics, economics, marketing, accounting and finance, etc. On the other hand, the sector management group had sectors, like Agriculture, Public Health, Transportation, Education, Power, Rural Development, Public Administration and Political Systems. These sectors were not even truly public sector domains. They were principally government sectors where there were no jobs for the graduates of the Institute.,under the Kanpur Indo-American Programme (KIAP).,Courtesy: Wikipedia,By the end of the fifties when India was busy in nation building, she founded some institutes of technology, also known as institutes of national importance. A choice then was clear before policy makers. Either they could have continued with commerce education or allowed management education to flourish in traditional universities or they would have adopted American MBA model. The American MBA model was being widely adopted and India has already adopted engineering model of the United States; therefore, it is no brainer that India went for the American MBA model of management education.,Mission, Method and Men,Although the Indian Institute of Management, Lucknow had leadership problems that hindered the growth of the institution, the bigger problem was its location. Unfortunately, the many subsequent IIMs suffered from locational disadvantage. Lucknow is the political hub of North India. However, the location of the fourth IIM was questionable as Lucknow hardly had a strong industrial base. Although the Chief Minister Narayan Datt Tiwary wanted to develop Lucknow and its surrounding areas as a modern industrial complex, the ground reality was far from it. Unlike the IIMs at Calcutta, Ahmedabad and Bangalore that had a reasonably acceptable client system, Lucknow as a city missed it substantially.,IIMs and their Locations,The KIL group of the IIMs was established in the eighties and nineties. The IIM Lucknow was founded in 1984, while the IIM Kozhikode and Indore were established in 1996. These IIMs are large and well developed by now. They figure well in Indian league tables. However, they are yet not recognised worldwide. Their main problem is their location. They cope with this problem by having their satellite campuses in metro cities. Their alumni base is small and most alumni have yet not reached the highest echelon of the corporate world. These IIMs are also unable to attract the best faculty, especially foreign trained.,The beginning of management education was, however, not glorious. In the 1880s, private business colleges emerged around New York and Boston to meet lower level personnel needs. By the end of the nineteenth century, there were over 500 such colleges in America. These colleges taught subjects like bookkeeping, arithmetic and penmanship (i.e., art of writing as typewriters were yet not available). The quality of education was of dubious nature. There were few regular faculty and those who taught had no standard qualifications. Similarly, there were no well defined eligibility criteria for admission. It is evident that the focus of education was narrow. It was useful for producing clerks, not business leaders.,Courtesy: IIM Ahmedabad,Prof Murthy also realised the need for inviting internationally trained faculty to teach the PGP courses. He was quite successful in that. A host of faculty members from foreign countries, especially the United States joined the Institute as visiting faculty and regular faculty. They started making a change in the functioning of the Institute and added to its brand value. He also invited senior managers from the industry to teach at the Institute. This further improved industry-institute interface and increased relevance in the PGP teaching. Over a period, the sectoral management orientation decreased and the IIMB started looking more like its peers, i.e., the IIMA and IIMC.,Indian Institutes of Management: A Tale of Two Start-up IIMs,University of Michigan,The first committee to review the performance of the IIMs was established in the leadership of Mr HP Nanda in 1981. Among other things, the committee recommended to establish additional two IIMs. Finally, one IIM at Lucknow was cleared by the central government.,Ajit himself was a lifelong learner. He did his PhD dissertation while working. He also completed his evening MBA from the International Management Institute, New Delhi, where he became a professor later. Most intriguingly, he finished his MSc from London School of Economics, when he was in London with his wife, Rashmi, who was managing an SBI branch over there. Ajit loved investing in books and journals. He had developed a rich library. His reading was in-depth as well as wide. He could talk with ease and authority about so many topics and make them interesting. He loved travelling far and wide. He travelled through most of the countries of Europe and several countries in the Americas.,The city of Bangalore emerged as the IT capital of the nation. Eventually, it has emerged as the hub of start-ups. Other industries like electronics, aviation, manufacturing, biotechnology, textile, etc. are also prominent in the economy of Bangalore. It has also emerged as a hub of start-ups.  In fact, Bangalore has emerged as a more vibrant city than Kolkata and Ahmedabad. Hence, the client system of Bangalore pushed the IIMB to focus on software management and innovation. It also provided rich consulting and training opportunities to the Institute. Although the late starter, the IIMB was able to catch up with the other two IIMs. Thus, the trinity of the IIM A, B, and C emerged and occupied the top notches in the league table.,These reports forced business schools to introspect and come out with a slew of innovations to make business education theoretically and methodologically more relevant and useful. The Ford Foundation also provided financial support to improve the quality of curriculum through research at certain prominent business schools in America.,In 1972, a committee headed by Ravi Matthai recommended the establishment of a third IIM at Bangalore (now Bengaluru). The location was reasonable as Bangalore was a metropolitan city of South India. Although the committee did not recommend any specific character of the new IIM, it was destined to be distinct from its two forerunners. As the early seventies was politically dominated by the socialist ideology, it decided to part ways from the IIMA and IIMC. It is interesting to note that the Memorandum of Articles of the IIMB was same as that of the other two IIMs. But, its philosophy and operating mechanisms were diametrically divergent.,The Socialist India,The first three IIMs (Calcutta, Ahmedabad, and Bangalore) were established in different metropolises. The next three IIMs (Lucknow, Indore, and Kozhikode) were founded in different state capitals. Now there are twenty IIMs and most of the third generation IIMs have poor locations, such as Kashipur, Sirmaur, Gaya, Ranchi, Udaipur, Sambalpur, Jammu, Am
