nion favoured India. Hence, there was no question of seeking American assistance in establishing the third IIM. The Soviet Union did not have any tradition of a business school. Its centralised economy did not need one. So, the Institute was established without a mentor. There was thus no ideological support for programme design & development and financial support for faculty development. The involvement of the industry in the conceptualisation and development was also negligent. These were the early years of designing and developing management education in India. Probably, the IIMB learned it the hard way.,Prof Doshi took inspiration from the gardens of Bangalore, temple of Maduri, and architecture of Fatehpur Sikri in designing the different buildings of the campus.  Of course, he was greatly influenced by his experience of designing the IIMA campus. His viewed learning as an open, social and interactive process. Accordingly, he designed a campus that facilitates these values. His creation is a mixture of traditional and modern architecture.,What is then the remedy? I do not intend to provide any. I critically examine the case method and point out that it has its limitations in developing an effective decision maker and manager. Academicians therefore have to look beyond the case method.,”,In Europe, management education was flourishing in Germany on the one hand and France, Italy and Spain on the other hand. The focus on management education in Germany was on accounting and finance, while France, Italy and Spain emphasised law and economics. However, these countries hardly had any influence on the Indian education system.,in 1959. Thus, IITs were established in east, west, north and south of India. All these IITs were recognised as institutes of national importance and were enacted by an Act of Parliament. IIT Kharagpur was established after American universities, especially Massachusetts of Technology, Boston. IIT Mumbai was helped by financial and technical assistance from the USSR. In the same vein, IIT Madras (Now Chennai) was supported by financial and technical support from West Germany. On the other hand, IIT Kanpur had a formal collaboration with a consortium of nine US universities, namely,View are personal.,,,His untimely departure is an incalculable loss to management academics, the practicing world and the student community.,September 9, 2018,Only in 1949, the National Scheme of Management Studies was implemented and British Institute of Management was created. Consequently, the management programmes were developed and were taught only in technical and commercial colleges. Business education was treated as vocational education and at diploma level. It was not offered even at the under graduate level. In other words, management education at best was perfunctory in the British higher education system, which was devoid of serious management education till two business schools were established at the universities of London and Manchester in the mid-sixties.,August 29, 2018,Dr Kamla Chowdhry was a professor of behavioural science at ATIRA. She was also a close friend of Dr Vikram Sarabhai. Both of them were convinced that the management school should be in Ahmedabad, not Bombay and Vikram could make it possible through his leadership. The FF wanted the business school of UCLA to be an academic partner of the new institution. However, again Kamla Chowdhry played a key role here. She had good contacts with Harvard professors and felt that HBS would be a better partner. Again, Vikram used his influence and replaced the UCLA business school with the HBS.,December 19, 2018,January, 1950, India became a democratic, secular republic and the constitution of India came into effect. As per the Constitution, education was in the state list and it was thus the primary responsibility of any state to provide education to its denizens.,Western India was mooted, Dr Vikram Sarabhai got interested in it. He  was already involved with the creation of strategic institutions like the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) and Physical Research Laboratory (PRL). He had deep linkages with the central government and was personally known to Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru.,Anup Kumar Singh, PhD,I propose to conclude this post by raising a complex question, “How the start-up IIMs could achieve and maintain their top positions in India and why could they not enter the league of top business schools internationally?” The answer to the first part of the question is: the start-up IIMs were experimenting and innovating. They could attract high quality students in the PGP. They developed a strong base of successful alumni. Last but not the least; they gave autonomy and academic freedom to their faculty. The answer to the second part of the question is somewhat complex. The start-up IIMs were not very strong in research and internationalisation. They were gratified with their education and training success. There were no internal or external reasons or demands to do high quality research. As India herself was inward looking till the eighties, the start-up IIMs followed the suit. They did not visualise comparing and competing internationally. Consequently, they are a paradox: national champions, but international laggards.,The image is not mine.,century soon realised that Indian universities suffer from low quality and are unable to establish themselves as vanguards of research and scholarship. They wanted higher education institutions like Oxford, Paris and Bologna universities. They thought of a ‘University of Research’, focussing on research and post graduate studies. Jamshetji N Tata presented a plan to Lord Curzon to found a research focussed institution in 1899 by the British Government and offered to make some financial contribution towards it. It was supposed to be a sort of public private partnership. However, the British Government was not aligned with the vision of Mr Tata. His vision was that the institution would conduct research that would solve industrial and societal problems. It was in sync with the growing industrialisation of India. But, the imperial rulers were not convinced about the idea. They were satisfied with the status quo. They were not in favour of conferring the status of university to the proposed institution. Eventually, William Ramsay was appointed to give his recommendations on the proposed institution. The Ramsay Report on the proposed institution suggested that it should be called an institute and it should do research in the different fields of science. After several years of efforts by the Tata family and conflicts between the Tata family and the British Government, the Indian Institute of Science was established in 1909 and started functioning during 1911-12. However, it focussed only on a few subjects of natural science. It included engineering and social science disciplines only in 1947. The establishment of Indian Institute of Science shed light on two facts. First, it was concerned with higher education and research. Second, it provided a viable alternative to the prevalent university system.,The IIMA,MIT,A rich, vibrant and diverse client system is critical for survival and excellence of a management institution. A business school must be embedded within its client system for a host of reasons. Most importantly, the purpose of a management institution is to serve its client system. In turn, the client system also grows with the help of an institute. It is imperative that the client system must be involved in establishing and promoting a business school. As business organisations are the primary beneficiary of a business school, they must invest in it. Further, there must be the representatives of the client system in the governing board to provide direction, resources and feedback to a business school. Ideally, the client system must be engaged in everything that a management institution does.,Carnegie Institute of Technology,India is the largest provider of management education only after the United States. Although India was a late entrant in the field of management education, it made significant strides over a period of six decades or so. Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) played a vital role in disseminating management ideas to youth and practicing managers. However, their roles and contributions in management education are questioned from time to time. As India today has twenty IIMs, will they be trailblazers of management education? In this series, I propose to explicate the historical development of IIMs and examine future directions. In the first post of the series, I explore higher education before the IIMs came in existence.,st,in 1959 as an institute of national importance by an Act of Parliament. Prof Mahalanobis played a significant role in planning Indian economy through the Planning Commission that was the pivot of developments from the 50s to 90s. Though he was a professor at Kolkata University, he preferred to found the ISI to complete mission given to him by the Government of India. Once again, the vulnerability of the university system was exposed and it was felt that an independent institute is academically and intellectually preferable to achieve missions and goals established by the Planning Commission.,Massive industrialisation, enormous trade and commerce, and proliferation of business organisations necessitated skilled personnel to meet burgeoning needs. Different countries responded to the demand for personnel for industries differently within Europe and across the Atlantic.,democratic republic’.  Emergency was wrought with atrocities, abolition of civil liberties and autocracy. As a result, she was thrown out of power in 1977 by joint opposition forum – Janta Party. However, the coalition government could not rule beyond two years and Mrs Gandhi came into power in 1980 again with a two third majority. This time again, she went for nationalisation of banks. Large company entrepreneurs and multinational companies were treated with disdain. Trade unions became quite powerful. The Indian economy was still looking inward. However, she was more pragmatic Prime Minister this time and relaxed modestly the socialist regime. But, it was too less too late. In this political economy, the seeds of the third IIM were sown.,When Mrs Gandh
 returned to power in 1979, she more or less continued with her previous economic policies, with some modifications here and there. By the mid-70s, the Eastern, Western and Southern regions of India had one Indian Institute of Management each. It was now the turn of the North India to get its share of IIMs. In the early eighties, the Indian National Congress ruled both the Uttar Pradesh and central governments. As Uttar Pradesh was the most populous and politically vital state, it was a deserving candidate. In 1984, Uttar Pradesh (undivided states of Uttar Pradesh and Uttrakhand) was given the fourth IIM and the state government decided that it should be located in Lucknow.,Indian Institutes of Management: Pre-IIM Management Education,The Sloan School of Management (SSM) and Harvard Business School (HBS) are situated on the two sides of the Charles river in Boston. Both are highly reputed business schools. However, they are poles apart in many respects. The HBS is one of the oldest business schools, characterised by close contacts with top industrialists and business leaders, focus on general management and the case study method as the main pedagogical tool. At Harvard University, each school has lots of freedom and acts almost like an independent academic institution. Thus, the HBS developed its unique culture that was more practice oriented. On the other hand, the MIT Sloan School of Management,  established in 1950,  was more academic in its orientation. Its main strengths were in systems thinking, quantitative analysis and rigorous research. It did not adopt the case study method at all. Its academic climate was greatly influenced by its umbrella organisation MIT, that was highly academic in nature.,In the late 19,Towards the end of the nineteenth century, business leaders in the United States realised that the business had really become complex and big. It requires a set of varied skills among young American who can provide leadership and manage the burgeoning complexity of business. This was not being done either by traditional collegiate system or by private business colleges. Thus, there was a void to be filled by higher educational institutions. The need for business education was felt by business owners as well as top managers and they voiced their concerns at several forums.,Business leaders were not only ready to absorb management graduates, but they were also willing to give financial support to the universities to establish business schools. The first such school was the Wharton Business School that was financially supported by Joseph Wharton, who was an influential business leader and strongly advocated for the provision of business education that not only provides technical skills, but also broadens the worldview of students. He gave one hundred thousand dollars to the University of Pennsylvania for this purpose.,The late Prof Ishwar Dayal was the founding Director of the Indian Institute of Management, Lucknow. He had rich industry experience at Mettal Box before joining the Indian Institute of Management, Calcutta. Then he moved to the Indian Institute of Management, Ahmedabad.  Later, he was the Director, Indian Institute of Public Administration and Dean of the International Management Institute, New Delhi. He advocated contextualising management concepts and practices in the Indian setting. He emphasised clinical approach to the study of management. He also stressed the case study method in the teaching of management. He was one of the doyens of management and administrative studies. However, when he joined the Institute, he was at the fag end of his career. While he was conceptually clear about institution building, he found it difficult to attract competent faculty and to create a distinct identity for the institution. The initial group of faculty was diverse and they mostly hailed from the non-IIM institutions. As he was the Director for only four years, he had limited time to make an impact and to build a lasting culture.,Emergence of Indian Institute of Science,There were four partners in establishing the IIMA. The state government provided the land for the campus. The FF paid for foreign collaboration. The industry paid for buildings. The central government paid for recurring grants and any financial deficits. Eventually, the central government became the main promotor. Other partners went into the background. The IIMA was established in 1962 with Dr Vikram Sarabhai as its honorary Director and Dr Jivraj Mehta as its Chairman. Its PGP was launched in 1964. Dr Sarabhai continued as an honorary Director almost for four years. The first formal Director of the Institute was Ravi Matthai, who was earlier a professor at the IIMC.,Indian Institutes of Management (now onwards the IIMs) are iconic higher education institutions. The idea – conceived in the mid-fifties by the Government of India that –  is still being implemented. There were just two IIMs in the sixties and now they have grown to become 20. It is likely that this number will grow in the future. In this post, I endeavour to survey the characteristic features of the IIMs and examine similarities and differences among them.,When India and China were performing so well, the Europe was struggling to meet with basic requirements of life. Post Roman Empire, the Europe suffered economically and culturally. It lived in the dark ages for many centuries. Not much happened in the Europe till 16,Ajit was not just a great teacher, he was a kind, empathetic and compassionate human being. He trusted people so much. Of course, he was not naïve. He might have been sometimes fooled by some. However, his way of living was trusting others. When asked for help, he would not disappoint anyone. Many times, he went out of the way to support others. He was a fiercely independent man. Nevertheless, he believed in investing in the relationships. His friends, including me, grieve his loss immensely. He worked with many organisations. Sometimes he followed his wife who was transferred from time to time in the SBI. Sometimes, she followed him. Anyways they made life long friends everywhere.,Prof Anup Kumar Singh,All great business schools likewise have eminent locations. Good examples of the location of such business schools are: Harvard (Boston), Stanford (San Jose), Booth Chicago (Chicago), Kellogg (Chicago), LBS (London), INSEAD (Fontainebleau), and HEC (Paris). The location entails an eco-system of varied educational institutions that complements and supplements the intellectual climate of a business school.,In the 19,After Independence, education was in the state list of constitution. Not surprisingly, the university model yielded poor results because it suffered from deficit of resources, politicisation of governance of universities and structural constraints in producing high quality. Quality and employability of its graduates remained low. Nevertheless, more than 90% students studies under the university system. Further, the University Grants Commission, established in 1956, as a body for coordination and funding of universities, failed to reform, enhance and increase the competitiveness of universities.,The case study method in management education is both fact and fiction. It is based on an event or life experience of a manager. However, it is dramatised and presented like a story to arouse the interest of the student community. Further, the case is slashed at a decision point where the case writer thinks the reader would face a fork or get intrigued. Decision making in managerial life is a continuous process and one decision leads to another. The continuity of decision making is not reflected in a typical case.,century, university leaders were under duress from external and internal stakeholders to commence a programme in business education. Internally, university leaders noticed that a majority of their students were joining business organisations after completing their studies. It forced them to think that there was some disconnect between their education and employment opportunities out there. Hence, their institution should offer a programme that prepared the students for the business world. Externally, business organisations experienced unprecedented growth during this period and there was a big requirement of managers at all levels, especially at the middle level. Business leaders expected the universities to supply requisite managerial personnel to them.,Skill development involves the emotions of a learner because his personal involvement in the learning process is intense. He moves from a lack of awareness of a skill to the mastery of the skill. Initially, his self-confidence is less; consequently, he is anxious, cautious, worried and diffident. Gradually, he develops confidence and anxiety gives way to reassurance. Finally, when he has achieved skill mastery, his emotional state is characterised by poise, happiness and hopefulness. Skill development is a time consuming process. Depending on the nature of a skill, the development can take place from months to years. Further, the nature of training of a skill may vary from one level to another. Achieving mastery entails long training and hard work spread over a long period of time.,Agrarian communities were bucolic in nature. Only a small fraction of the population lived in cities. They engaged in agriculture, animal husbandry, handicraft, construction, etc. Further, they were more or less autonomous. People within the communities bartered with one another. Trade and commerce across communities was at low ebb. Of course, some trade happened across countries. Two countries – India and China – flourished during this aeon. They were leaders on economic, cultural and intellectual fronts.,’ to a ‘sovereign,,/,Like the two IIMs, the IIMB had to have a two year post graduate programme in management (PGP). Even today, a two-year programme in management or MBA is the fulcrum of a management institute. The Institute launched the PGPM in 1974. However, the client system of this programme was the public sector, not the corporate world. The student stakeholder was the same as that of IIMA and IIMC. Nevertheless, the recruiter stakeholder was different – the Public Sector Enterprises and the government. The basic curricular architecture was a typical PGP curriculum. However, the students were required to take two elective courses in the public sector field, so that they are ready for the public sector enterprises. The student group, on the contrary, was not ready for this scheme of things. Their dream was to join the corporate sector where they are paid better and have an opportunity to realise their talents. It was a paradoxical situation. The Institute was trying to add a value that was not valued by the students.,The IIMs always needed high calibre faculty who are in serious scarcity. Faculty deficiency is around 30% to 40%. As the IIMs are established independent of the University system (no truck with University Grants Commission), they have the pros and cons of  faculty effectiveness. The IIMs have far greater autonomy and try to achieve their mission, using their autonomy and resourcefulness. They select foreign trained Indians and PhD students trained in leading institutions in India and are able to pay them decently. The mandate to the faculty is to be focussed on practice and engaged with the industry – their client system. Their teaching load is on the lesser side as compared to their university counterparts. Consequently, they do very well in teaching, training and consulting. However, they unwittingly perform below par in research and extension activities.,amendment to the Constitution was introduced which changed the character of India from  a ‘,The British Scenario,By opening satellite campuses and facilities, the IIMs achieve the objective of integration with the client system. However, this approach has numerous problems. The first problem is that it results in high overheads of extra personnel, infrastructure, and faculty. In addition, there is the loose unity of command. The satellite campus leader may have priorities that can be quite different from the main campus Director. A second problem is that two campuses invariably result in two cultures. Often, the satellite campus is given distinct objectives. For example, the satellite campus of the IIM Lucknow was tasked with Executive PGP and executive education. Faculty thus thought and worked differently and conflicts between the main campus and the satellite campus ensued.,Two Business Schools of Boston,University of California, Berkeley,Prof Ramaswamy was a professor of management at the Jamnalal Bajaj  Institute of Management Studies, Bombay. However, he was famously known as Cartman Ramaswamy. He has a keen interest in the social sector. He developed an efficient bullock cart, which reduced the drudgery of bullocks.  His philosophy was amply reflected in the functioning of the IIMB. As the founder Director, he led the Institute for a decade and was able to translate successfully his vision into reality.,The rest IIMs are in a nascent stage and are in the process of developing their infrastructure and academic programmes. They may be valued within India, but they may take a long time to acquire global stature. They are struggling to smooth teething problems. Most of these IIMs are situated in geographical locations which do not have a strong industrial base. Subsequently,  faculty and students have limited opportunities of learning and experimentation. However, a few IIMs of this strategic group may break out and do well for themselves.,The Response to the Poor Location Problem,The Post Ford Foundation Report Period,In addition, the IIMs are active in management development since the beginning.  They offer general management as well as functional management programmes for middle and senior managers. Such programmes help them remain in touch with their client system. Moreover, they help build deep networks with business organisations that in turn results in more consulting. After the PGP, management development programmes are the second largest source of revenue for them.,Business education in the sixties, thus, entered a new phase of development and its character changed forever.,The IIMs provided a pivotal role to faculty in institution building. They emerged as a faculty driven institution. The Faculty Council in which all faculty members participated is the final decision making body. The Director of the IIMs is not a leader who makes his own decision. Rather, he is one who implements the decisions collectively made by the faculty. Faculty centricity sometimes has adverse consequences. Decisions may be taken to protect faculty interest, and not to promote institutional interests. Politics and jockeying for power may be quite prevalent. Today, effective academic institutions aim to be more student centric.,The IIMs are expensive by Indian standards.  The two year PGP costs a student around Rs 20 Lakh that is not a small amount. However, the IIMs aver that they provide less expensive management education in comparison to their Western counterparts. Any ways their fees is much higher in comparison to their Indian counterparts. Their tuition fees are not regulated unlike their Indian counterparts. They have that advantage. For a typical student, the cost of education is important. She cannot get educated at any cost, but at a cost. Some may argue that if business is about the market, then why business education should not be subjected to the market.,In 1950, the School of Industrial Management (now Sloan Management School) at Massachusetts Institute of Technology was established with general financial support from Alfred P Sloan Foundation. The Sloan Management School was more theory driven. Its focus was quantitative and its emphasised systems theory. Both these schools – Harvard and Sloan  based out of Boston – were to play an important role in developing management education in India. Till the end of 40s, business education inexorably grew  both at the undergraduate and postgraduate level.,socialist,The influence of MIT Sloan School of Management was palpable on the IIMC. The faculty and students had a high degree of freedom at the IIMC. The focus was more on academic rese
rch and on areas like economics, production and quantitative methods. The client system was mostly government based, covering eastern and northeast India.,By the end of fifties, two models of higher education emerged in India: the university model and the institute model. The university model was a legacy of the affiliating university, which was cost effective and meant to providing access to a large number of students. The British Raj had transferred education to its provinces under diarchy in 1919; thus, education became the responsibility of a provincial state. The imperial government did not allow the states to widen their higher educational institutions.,Kharagpur,On 15,Case Institute of Technology,Learning is an important step towards wisdom. It is a complex process and there myriad ways to attain it. The case method is indeed one of them. Today it has achieved an iconic status. Nevertheless, its popularity cannot and should not prevent us from critical examination. The case method has emerged as an significant method in law and management education almost for a century. In the law education, the purpose of the case method was to discover the principle of law, based on the examination of appellate cases, using the Socratic Method. It helped law students in the United States, where the principles of law were not codified. The purpose was to help the students to think like a lawyer.,Later, Indian Statistical Institute was established under the leadership of Prof,There is a popular story about the relation between the two business schools.  Prof Edgar Schein joined the MIT Sloan School of Management as a young professor and went to his department head to discuss his plan of research. Ed explored with his department head what he should do as a scholar. Promptly came the reply from the head, “Whatever you wish to do, please do. But don’t do the things that they do across the river.” The story amply shows that the two business schools were very different in their academic orientation.,Skill development has five steps: awareness of a skill and its various components, understanding of each component and practice on it, practice on all components in an integrated way, practice of skill till certain level is achieved, the measurement of skill and subsequent action plan for the improvement of the skill. Skill development is more about action and less about knowledge. Therefore, it requires lesser time for knowledge acquisition and greater time for practice and improvement.,Private Business College Period:,The IIMs admit only Indian students. Like any government higher education institution, they reserve 49.5% seats for students from backward communities. This affirmative action has its own pros and cons for quality of management education. Unlike prominent business schools like the HBS, the LBS or INSEAD, the IIMs do not take a single international student. However, it is a political decision and the IIMs can do little about it.,Abhi Ishq Ke Imtihan Aur Bhi Hain,The Third Generation IIMs,Way back 1903, the Presidency College (now Presidency University) – affiliated to Kolkata University-introduced commerce education. At that time, Kolkata was both political and commercial capital of India. A decade later, Sydenham College of Commerce – named after Lord Sydenham of Combe, the then Governor of Bombay –  was established in Mumbai.  Now the college is more famous for a locale for Bollywood films than for its contribution to commerce education.,Kanpur,When India became free, Pt Jawarharlal Nehru, educated at Cambridge University and internationalist, was seriously engaged in nation building through the Planning Commission and his approach of development characterised by science and technology. Being influenced by the Bombay Plan and the centralised model of economic development of the Soviet Russia, he thought that Indian industries cannot grow and prosper unless it has well trained technical manpower. In addition, India needed higher education institutions that would conduct high quality research. While he was deeply influenced by central planning model of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR), he also appreciated high quality American higher education institutions.,When Prof Philip joined the Institute, the major challenge was managing discipline among faculty and staff, not academic integration. He was a disciplinarian and experienced at managing industrial relations. Most of his time went into managing people. Although the economic and socio-political climate was changing in India, its impact was yet not perceptible in the mission and objects of the IIMB.,In the 60s and 70s, Calcutta was afflicted by naxalism and the flight of capital started. Several multinationals started withdrawing their offices and production facilities from the city. After the 1971 war at the time of creation of Bangladesh, millions of refugees entered West Bengal, especially in Calcutta and strained its economy. In the late 70s, the Communists formed the government and it further hurt the economy. In other words, Calcutta as a business hub was deteriorating and declining fast.,in 1958, and both IIT,She came out through the Congress Working Committee with a ten-point agenda to re-centre Indian economy. These points were: nationalisation of banks; nationalisation of general  insurance organisations; ceilings on urban property and income; curbs on business monopolies; public distribution of food grains; rapid implementation of land reforms; provision of land sites for housing of the rural poor; nationalisation of import and export trade, and abolition of princely privileges and privy purses. She went ahead with her agenda and became a national hero. Then she pursued ruthlessly her socialist ideology. In 1971, with her slogan of ‘Garibi Hatao’, she came into power with a two third majority. In the same year, during the Bangladesh War of Independence, India and Pakistan has a major confrontation. In this period, a large number of refugees enter India. The war and refugee problems caused serious economic difficulties for the country.,Although the IIMs share a common brand and ownership pattern, they widely vary from one another as well. In fact, they can be divided into three strategic groups: the first generation IIMs (Ahmedabad, Bangalore and Calcutta – ABC); the second generation IIMs (Kozhikode, Indore and Lucknow – KIL); and, the third generation IIMs (the rest IIMs). The ABC group of the IIMs, established in the sixties and seventies, is now fully developed. These IIMs are geographically situated in business hubs and integrated with the industry. They are ranked among top 50 business schools in the world. They are exemplars for the rest IIMs.,Like British universities, American universities had their reservation about business education throughout the nineteenth century. Educational leaders felt that universities are not the place for teaching business. They are in the business of knowledge, not skills and business practices. Universities produce thinkers, not traders and business practitioners. They were comfortable providing professional education in the fields of theology, medicine, law and engineering. For them, business was no profession. Like their British counterparts, they also acknowledged lack of curriculum and pedagogy for management education. The university community also did not have a positive image of business and commerce. Consequently, they decided to keep an arm’s length from business education.,When a business school is devoid of a robust client system, it responds in two ways. Firstly, it pretends that it can be effective without a client system. It consequently becomes introverted and insulated. Faculty members do not focus on consulting and training. They also shun applied research. Their teaching becomes bookish.  Secondly, a business school develops a false client system. This strategy is often adopted by several IIMs that start believing the government as their client system. They do consulting and training for governm

